'''OpenEMR'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.open-emr.org/ |title=OpenEMR Project Website |accessdate=2011-10-01}}</ref> is a [[Free and open source software|Free and Open Source]], [[Practice management]] and [[Electronic Medical Records]] software application. It is '''ONC Complete Ambulatory EHR certified'''<ref name=mod_cert>{{cite web |url=http://oncchpl.force.com/ehrcert/EHRProductDetail?id=a0A3000000LW494EAD&retURL=%2Fehrcert%2FEHRProductSearch&setting=Ambulatory |title=ONC Complete Ambulatory EHR Certified |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref><ref name=mod_cert_article>{{cite web |url=http://openhealthnews.com/hotnews/openemr-41-achieves-full-meaningful-use-certification |title=OpenEMR 4.1 Achieves Full 'Meaningful Use' Certification |author=Maduro, Roger |date=2011-08-22 |accessdate=2011-10-01}}</ref><ref name=mod_cert_article_second>{{cite web |url=http://linuxmednews.com/1313842854/index_html |title=OpenEMR achieves full ONC certification |author=Cahn, Jack |date=2011-08-20 |accessdate=2011-10-01}}</ref> and it features fully integrated [[electronic medical records]], [[practice management]], scheduling, electronic billing, internationalization, and free support.  It can run on [[Microsoft]] systems, [[Unix-like]] systems ([[Linux]], [[UNIX]], and [[BSD]] systems), [[Mac OS X]] and other platforms.

OpenEMR is one of the most popular free electronic medical records in use today with over 3,700 downloads per month.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sourceforge.net/project/stats/detail.php?group_id=60081&ugn=openemr&type=prdownload&mode=12months&file_id=0 |title=OpenEMR Sourceforge Download Statistics |accessdate=2010-02-23}}</ref> The community maintains the official OpenEMR web site at open-emr.org.<ref name="mod_cert_article_second"/><ref name=sourceforge>{{cite web |url=http://sourceforge.net/projects/openemr/ |title=OpenEMR on Sourceforge|accessdate=2011-08-19}}</ref>

== History ==

OpenEMR was originally developed by Synitech and version 1.0 was released in June 2001 as MP Pro (MedicalPractice Professional).<ref name=the_openemr_community>{{cite web |url=http://www.openmedsoftware.org/wiki/The_OpenEMR_Community |title=The OpenEMR Community|accessdate=2012-02-25|author=Donahue,Margaret|date=2006-02-16}}</ref> Much of the code was then reworked for [[HIPAA]] compliance and improved security, and the product was reintroduced as OpenEMR version 1.3 a year later, in July 2002.<ref name=openemr_release>{{cite web |url=http://linuxmednews.com/linuxmednews/1025910430/index_html |title=OpenEMR Released |accessdate=2009-11-26 |author=Stack, Matthew |date=2002-07-05}}</ref>  It became an open source project and was registered on SourceForge.net on August 13, 2002.<ref name=sourceforge>{{cite web |url=http://sourceforge.net/projects/openemr/ |title=OpenEMR on Sourceforge|accessdate=2012-01-27}}</ref> The project evolved through version 2.0 and the Pennington Firm (Pennfirm) took over as its primary maintainer in 2003.<ref name=the_openemr_community /> Walt Pennington transferred the OpenEMR software repository to [[SourceForge]] in March 2005, where it remains today.<ref name=first_sf_commit>{{cite web |url=http://openemr.git.sourceforge.net/git/gitweb.cgi?p=openemr/openemr;a=commit;h=7080e87bbabb66d0456d75c3121f71bd6912572d |title=OpenEMR First Sourceforge Commit|accessdate=2012-01-28}}</ref>  Mr. Pennington also established Rod Roark, Andres Paglayan and James Perry, Jr. as administrators of the project.<ref name=the_openemr_community />  Walt Pennington, Andres Paglayan and James Perry eventually took other directions and were replaced by Brady Miller in August 2009.<ref name=sourceforge_openemr>{{cite web |url=http://sourceforge.net/projects/openemr/ |title=Sourceforge OpenEMR Project |accessdate=2011-10-01}}</ref>  So at this time Rod Roark and Brady Miller are the project's co-administrators.<ref name=sourceforge_openemr />

