== Deployments ==
Because this is an open source project that does not register its users, it is very difficult to estimate the number of practitioners that are using this software. In the US, it has been estimated that there are more than 5,000 installations of OpenEMR in physician offices and other small healthcare facilities serving more than 30 million patients.<ref name="openemr_continues_to_grow">{{cite web |url=http://www.openhealthnews.com/hotnews/openemr-continues-grow-popularity-and-use |title=OpenEMR Continues to grow in Popularity and Use |accessdate=2012-12-20 |author=Groen, Peter |date=2012-12-18}}</ref> Internationally, it has been estimated that OpenEMR is installed in over 15,000 healthcare facilities, translating into more than 45,000 practitioners using the system which are serving greater than 90 million patients.<ref name="openemr_continues_to_grow"/> The Peace Corps plan to incorporate OpenEMR into their EHR system in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.govhealthit.com/news/peace-corps-plans-ehr-system-2013 |title=Peace Corps plans EHR system in 2013 |accessdate=2012-02-03 |author=Mosquera, Mary |date=2012-02-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://linuxmednews.com/1328459378/index_html |title=Peace Corps Selects OpenEMR |accessdate=2012-02-05 |author=Cahn, Jack |date=2012-02-05}}</ref> Siaya District Hospital, a 220-bed hospital in rural Kenya, is using OpenEMR.<ref name="kenya_siaya_1">{{cite web |url=http://linuxmednews.com/1328842067 |title= MediGrail LLC Automates Siaya District Hospital in Rural Kenya with OpenEMR |accessdate=2012-02-10 |author=Sidhu, Yudhvir|date=2012-02-10}}</ref><ref name="kenya_siaya_2">{{cite web |url=http://www.openhealthnews.com/hotnews/siaya-district-hospital-kenya-goes-live-openemr |title= Siaya District Hospital in Kenya Goes Live With OpenEMR |accessdate=2014-04-14 |author=Groen, Peter|date=2012-04-08}}</ref><ref name="kenya_siaya_3">{{cite web |url=http://open-emr.org/wiki/index.php/OpenEMR_Success_Stories#Siaya_District_Hospital_in_Kenya_Goes_Live_With_OpenEMR_in_April_2012 |title=Siaya District Hospital in Kenya Goes Live With OpenEMR in April 2012 |accessdate=2012-06-13 |author=Sidhu, Yudhvir|date=2012-03-26}}</ref><ref name="kenya_siaya_4">{{cite web |url=http://open-emr.org/wiki/index.php/OpenEMR_Success_Stories#Siaya_District_Hospital_in_Kenya_Update_11_Jun_2012 |title=Siaya District Hospital in Kenya Update 11 Jun 2012 |accessdate=2012-06-13 |author=Sidhu, Yudhvir|date=2012-06-12}}</ref><ref name="kenya_siaya_5">{{cite web |url=http://www.openhealthnews.com/hotnews/open-source-emr-alternatives-kenya |title=Open Source EMR Alternatives for Kenya |accessdate=2012-12-20 |author=Groen, Peter|date=2012-11-21}}</ref> HP India is planning to utilize OpenEMR for their Mobile Health Centre Project.<ref name="india_hp_1">{{cite web |url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/2012/7/prweb9699462.htm |title=HP India Mobile Health Centre Project To Utilize OpenEMR |accessdate=2012-07-17 |date=2012-07-16}}</ref> There are also articles describing single clinician deployments<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emrandhipaa.com/emr-and-hipaa/2009/11/25/openemr-success-story/ |title=OpenEMR Success Story |accessdate=2009-12-14 |author=Holzer, Joe |date=2009-11-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://linuxmednews.com/1138557562/index_html |title=Using OpenEMR in Family Practice |accessdate=2009-12-14 |author=Leeds, Mark |date=2006-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oemr.org/2012/12/12/518/ |title=Going From Paper to Electronic: A Road Map |accessdate=2012-12-20 |author=Peterson, Diane |date=2012-12-12}}</ref> and a free clinic deployment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.healthcareguy.com/2009/11/15/guest-article-open-source-emrs-for-free-clinics/ |title=Guest Article: Open Source EMRs for free clinics |accessdate=2009-12-14 |author=Clifford, Kevin |date=2009-11-15}}</ref> Internationally, it is known that there are practitioners in Pakistan,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.tele-healthcare.org/2010/01/jaroka-electronic-health-record-system.html |title=Jaroka Electronic Health Record System provides opportunities for further Research and Analysis |accessdate=2010-01-23 |author=Mushtaq, Hina |date=2010-01-18}}</ref> Puerto Rico, Australia, Sweden, Holland, Israel, India,<ref name="india_hp_1" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://nagalandpost.com/ShowStory.aspx?npoststoryiden=UzEwMjQyOTE%3D-u5jpoTKCit0%3D |title=FPAI conducts training on OpenEMR |accessdate=2010-04-05 |author=DIMAPUR |date=2010-04-05}}</ref> Malaysia, Nepal, Indonesia, Bermuda, Armenia, Kenya,<ref name="kenya_siaya_1" /><ref name="kenya_siaya_2" /><ref name="kenya_siaya_3" /><ref name="kenya_siaya_4" /><ref name="kenya_siaya_5" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.prlog.org/12041984-openemr-presented-to-the-kenya-medical-association.html |title=OpenEMR presented to the Kenya Medical Association |accessdate=2012-12-20 |author=VoIP4Africa Ltd. |date=2012-12-17}}</ref> and Greece that are either testing or actively using OpenEMR for use as a free electronic medical records program.

== Architecture ==

OpenEMR is a "[[LAMP (software bundle)|LAMP]]" type of web based software application that uses a web server such as [[Apache HTTP Server|Apache]], [[MySQL]] as the database and [[PHP]] as its programming language.  As with most "LAMP" architecture, OpenEMR can run on [[Linux]], [[Unix]], [[BSD]], [[Mac OS X]], and [[Microsoft]] architectures.

== Certification ==

Both OpenEMR versions 4.1.0 (released on 9/23/2011) and 4.1.1 (released on 8/31/2012) have ONC Complete Ambulatory EHR Certification.<ref name="mod_cert"/><ref name="mod_cert_article"/><ref name="mod_cert_article_second"/><ref name="411_release"/> OpenEMR was certified by ICSA Labs<ref name="icsa_labs">{{cite web |url=http://www.icsalabs.com/ |title=ICSA Labs Website |accessdate=2012-12-20}}</ref> and the OEMR<ref name="oemr_org">{{cite web |url=http://www.oemr.org/ |title=OEMR Organization Website |accessdate=2012-12-20}}</ref> organization is a non-profit entity that manages/provides this certification.<ref name="mod_cert_article"/>

== Awards ==

OpenEMR received a 2012 Bossie Award in the "The Best Open Source Applications" category.<ref name="bossie_2012">{{cite web |url=http://www.infoworld.com/slideshow/65165/bossie-awards-2012-the-best-open-source-applications-202530#slide21 |title=Bossie Awards 2012: The best open source applications |accessdate=2012-09-20 |author=InfoWorld |date=2012-09-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2010155/10-award-winning-open-source-apps-to-try-today.html |title=10 award-winning open source apps to try today |accessdate=2012-09-21 |author=Noyes, Katherine |date=2012-09-20}}</ref>

== OEMR ==

OEMR<ref name="oemr_org"/> is a 501(c)(3) tax exempt entity that was organized in July, 2010 to support the OpenEMR project.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oemr.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/OEMR_2010-07-22_Organizational_Meeting.pdf |title=OEMR Organization Meeting Minutes (2012-07-22) |accessdate=2012-12-20 | date=2010-07-22}}</ref> OEMR is the entity that holds the ONC Complete Ambulatory EHR Certification with ICSA Labs<ref name="icsa_labs"/>.<ref name="mod_cert_article"/>

